deck_excerpt: Lunalight  / Ranking Tournament Multitoys Kelapa Gading 1st Place
deck_description:
Category: Tournament Meta Decks (Asian-English OCG)

Tournament Meta Decks are current-level Meta Decks that are capable of going up against the best of the best. These are curated lists that cannot be uploaded by regular users.

Creator: Kevin Haryono

Tournament: Ranking Tournament Multitoys Kelapa Gading – August 26th 2025

Placement: 1st Place

The idea of this deck is to try to get through all the negations or interruptions the opponent may have by using effects from the GY of the cards sent there. Using the Lightsworn strategy of sending cards to the GY, we can trigger the effects of Zombie monsters. The main concept is to send Wightspreader to be able to add Wightsworn and Wightprince, sending more cards to the GY and gradually summoning from the Extra Deck, forcing the opponent to use all their resources before the arrival of the two “Boss” monsters of the deck: Ween & King of the S. Alternatively, the deck can also win by resource advantage, since these are high ATK monsters. You will see the video once I upload it. For now, I’ll first play a version in Master Duel, which doesn’t include two monsters currently in the TCG and the Skull Servant spell card.

deck_excerpt: Can advantage control decks like Regenesis compete in Masterduel's cutthroat meta? Definitely!
deck_description:
Ever since Runick has been rendered helpless due to Maliss (banishing their monsters plusses them) and Ryzeal (Detonator can easily pop Fountain), I haven't had a proper "control advantage" deck to pilot on ladder. Can advantage control decks like Regenesis still compete in Masterduel's cutthroat meta full of combo juggernauts like Maliss and midrange monsters like Ryzeal? Definitely!

Regenesis is very simple to play and it has no combos, so I'm not making a detailed strategy guide on it. Just use the 20 handtraps simplify your opponent's gamestate, then outgrind them with your relentless Regenesis deck core!

This decklist features all the handtraps that hardcounter meta ladder strategies, like Artifact Lancea and Chaos Hunter (which has synergy with Regenesis since it's 2500ATK) for Maliss! Even your Regenesis monsters get sent to the graveyard during your opponent's turn, they all just return to your hand in the endphase, and their spells like "Regenesis" and "Code" can ressurect your monsters from the GY and Banishment! Not to mention that every single Regenesis monster is a massive beatstick, so you can also equalize your opponent's board in the battle phase by running everything over, especially with the 5000 ATK Regenesis Lord! 

Surprisingly, I've laddered way up the ranks with this deck in a Maliss and Ryzeal infested meta - it's a incredibly competent advantage control deck!

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

GLHF DUELISTS!

This is a very enjoyful to play deck that pushes and reinforces attendiveness and quick thinking. It can compete with SOME meta decks but you should expect to lose sometimes.

You can skip the below summary/monologue/thought process if you just want to understand the deck. 

Ashened and Volcanic are really fun archetypes to play around with in general. Unfortunately, the two of them alone have no competitive viability if you play against any modern competent deck. The two together start to create a somewhat playable strategy. Now, if we throw in a splashable competitive engine we're starting to really cook. There are two primary options: Snake-Eye and Fiendsmith. Snake-Eye being pyro makes it extremely ideal, because you can partial or full combo and have fodder for your Volcanic Emperor. However, without Original Sinful Spoils, the deck consistency causes the Snake-Eye cards to become bricky. Ideally you want your normal summon to advance your Volcanic or Ashened lines, not your splashable engine line. This is where I landed on Fiendsmith. Without Moon of the Closed Heaven, it's going to be weaker, but still solid. Our goal really isn't to have a Fiendsmith endboard. We use Fiendsmith much like Ryzeal does, we get as far as we can to draw out any hand traps or interruptions, then we go for our Ashened and/or Volcanic combo lines. 

Key things to understand:

  1. Fiendsmith, Volcanic, and Ashened are unique engines that can operate indepently of one another
  2. Always do Ashened lines last since most of the spells lock you out of the extra deck (except pyros)
  3. Exception to the Ashened lines last rule is Volcanic Emperor, since you can use Ashened cards to summon him from hand or grave.

Combos:

Fiendsmith - I'm just going to include the basic opening Engraver combo line and point out good times to add in volcanic 

  1. open Engraver
    1. activate to add Tract
    2. Tract add and discard Lurrie
    3. Lurrie effect to special itself from grave
    4. Link Requiem using Lurrie <--- can start volcanic lines here if you're comfortable with Fiendsmith interactions and aren't scared of Nib
    5. Requiem effect to summon Lacrima Crimson Tears
    6. Lacrima effect to send engraver
    7. Engraver effect to summon itself (return Lurrie to deck)
    8. Link Sequence using Lacrima and Engraver
    9. Sequence effect to summon Desirae <--- if you're confident in being able to execute full Volcanic to go for game (typically turn 2 or later), you can do FS Lacrima. Volcanic Emperor full burn on summon + Lacrima burn can easily hit your oppent for 2700-3200 or more depending on how many pyros have been banished by the time you summon Emperor
    10. Link Agnumday using Sequence and Desirae
    11. Agnumday effect to rez Desirae and attach Agnumday
    12. start Volcanic and/or Ashened

Volcanic - Volcanic unfortunately cannot stand by itself. There aren't many Volcanic only card combos. Volcanic can do a lot with other engine cards though. The most basic combos are 2+ cards. The most important thing to remember is that this engine wants to summon Volcanic Emperor and wants Volcanic Blaze Accelerator (VBA) and/or one of the traps on the board. 

  1. open Trooper + Volcanic Blaze Accelerator 
    1. normal Trooper
    2. add Rimfire by Trooper effect
    3. Activate Volcanic Blaze Accelerator by sending Blaze Accelerator to grave (you can activate VBA first, special Trooper, then normal Rimfire. i just like Trooper first to see what cards i can bait out. it's more important for VBA to stay on the field than Trooper)
    4. Special Rimfire by Volcanic Blaze Accelerator 
    5. here's where we have a lot of options. The main thing is to get Rimfire into the grave and send Emperor by it's effect. if you get this far, and have Ashened cards for Ashened combos, then you will have what you need to summon Emperor
      1. link summon Relinquished Anima using Rimfire -> Rimfire effect to banish itself and send Volcanic Emperor to the grave -> link summon lines you want. Can end on Accesscode talker or S:P depending on your other cards, opponent interruptions, etc etc
      2. link hiita -> same rimfire effect -> steal ash blossom or whatever -> move on from here (this is where there is a lot of wiggle room in the extra deck. you can take out the superpoly targets for more link cards like Promethean, Amblow, etc)
      3. start ashened lines and use trooper/rimfire as fusion mats
  2. VBA + opponent has a monster on the field
    1. activate VBA by sending Blaze Accelerator
    2. VBA effect to send rimfire to grave and remove opponent's monster
    3. Rimfire effect to banish itself and send Emperor
  3. VBA + Shell or Rimfire
    1. activate VBA by sending BA
    2. special shell or rimfire
    3. summon anima using the above
    4. use the above graveyard effect
      1. shell effect adds another shell to your hand from deck for 500 lp
      2. shell's in hand or on the field can be used for Ashened lines

Ashened: like Volcanic, Ashened doesn't really have 1 card starters, but it has a lot of 2+ card starters. most of the combos can be 1 ashened card + cards from the other engines

  1. Priestess + any pyro monster (this combo is why getting anywhere with the volcanic engine gets you the Ashened boss)
    1. normal priestess
    2. add Extinguishing
    3. Extinguishing effect to send Veidos from deck to grave
    4. Add Veidos to hand from grave
    5. Banish Extinguishing to summon Veidos the Dragon of Endless Darkness using other pyro, Priestess & Veidos
  2. Awakening of Veidos + priestess
    1. Activate Awakening - put Obisidim in opponent field spell zone
    2. add Veidos from deck to hand
    3. special priestess
    4. add King
    5. special King
    6. Activate Veidos to send Obsidim to grave and summon veidos to opponent field
    7. Veidos effect to add either Ashened trap (this is a dealer's choice situation. it's best to play the deck and learn what matchups necessitate which option)
    8. Obsidim effect to summon another priestess (Spear or Shaman are fine targets if you add them, but they feel awful to draw)
    9. King effect to special Hero

After all of the above, if Emperor is in grave or hand, Emperor effect to summon itself. banish pyros for more burn damage on summon. banish BA to summon Emperor if you don't have enough Pyro targets. On Emperor summon, activate effect to burn for all banished pyros and set a volcanic trap. Both Volcanic traps are amazing. Inferno is a negate by banishing a Volcanic from GY. Emission specials a volcanic or burns your oppent for 50% of the Attack of a pyro on your field or 100% of the attack for a pyro on your opponents field. using this second effect with veidos on your opponent's field or obsidim on your side of the field during your turn, can do massive damage. 

Superpoly gives your board a boost going first or second. Almarduke is specifically for Maliss (or any link focused strategy)

There are countless details I could add to fill out this description, but it's already so long. The deck really does have a lot of options and is incredibly fun to play. It struggles against the 20+ handtrap decks, but all rogue strategies do. At the end of the day, if you put the time in the learning the interactions with all of the engines here, you can pull of some crazy plays. Also, nobody plays either Volcanic or Ashened, so you can catch people offguard so easily.

Notes:

-Mulcharmy cards and Maxx C is not a problem. You can deck them out.

-lancea is the least of the problem since block dragon banish cards

-droll is the biggest problem since you need to add cards to your hand early combos

deck_description: there is 15 starters, 15 handtraps and techically 6 bricks (7 if you count primite fusion)

Mimighoul MASTER!

What can I say? This isn't exactly the deck I planned on reaching Master with this season, I was just playing it for fun. The list is not even optimal, as I don't have the third copy of Mimighoul Maker (and didn't want to spend more URs), so I replaced it with Mimighoul Charm (it is funny).

However, this deck keeps blowing my expectations out of the water - against all odds, between the slow-ish nature of the deck, Dominus Impulse shuting down most of our plays, and the terrible coin toss luck (went first 16 out of 42 games, ~38%), I was still able to get a 71% win ratio by winning ALL 16 games I went first. With this, I speedran through Diamond and got into Master, making it the fastest climb into Master with a Rogue deck I've ever had.

If you're not familiar with Mimighoul, is a gimmicky control strategy that aims to gift your opponent flip monsters with negative effects, and then forcing them to be flipped face-up. Mimighoul Dragon blows up their board, Mimighoul Archfiend makes them discard 1 and you draw 1, etc. You then combine these effects with cards such as:

  • Mimighoul Dungeon: the field spell, it's not only a consistency card but also locks the opponent out of their normal summon while they control a face-down monster.
  • Mimighoul Maker: It's a weird consistency card since it involves randomness, but it is very useful and also has a great GY effect to flip up the Mimighouls you give to your opponent when they special summon something.
  • Mimighoul Room: a great trap card, being a book of moon that also summons a Mimighoul from deck to either field. It is also good when combined with Dungeon (the monster summoned face-down cannot be flipped on the same turn, so the opponent is locked out of their normal summon).
  • Mimighoul Throne: Summons the Mimighoul Master from the deck, and then provides a non-targeting bounce. Master itself can also flip up the Mimighouls during the opponent's Main Phase.

It's very funny that Mimighoul Dragon outs some tough cards such as the The Unstoppable Exodia Incarnate, Chaos Angel, Links made with I:P Masquerena, etc. since it counts as their effect.

The Kashtira package is small but useful, especially since the Mimighoul effects trigger Kashtira Unicorn. Something similar happens with the Triple Tactics cards, with the Mimighouls making them live. Some people prefer a Fiendsmith package, but I like this variant.

In addition to adding the third copy of Maker, I would also replace Linkuriboh with Relinquished Anima in the Extra Deck if I had it, it could be more useful situationally. Kikinagashi Fucho could also be useful for Zeus plays sometimes.

Hope you enjoyed the deck! Let me hear your thoughts :)

deck_excerpt: First Version as of JUSH format - White Woods, Azamina, Demonsmith
deck_description:
I only recently learned this deck so it may come with improvements later
- I don't like the field spell so I did not run it
- If you need more spells/traps to maindeck then I also considered Dominus Purge as the entire White Woods and Demonsmith lines are unnaffected
- Without Moon it is harder to access Demonsmith but because of how valuable the engine is I just prefer to run it anyway with as many starters as possible, A Bao is basically the replacement to usa or Gryphon because neither of those are legal but it can also be used to revive a Rciela or Silvera to make Vengeance - Or just Summon back Silvis if you had to use it on your turn
- I have not tested the sideboard Diabell cards but they seem strong, I don't feel comfortable maindecking them when I don't know what their lines would look like but that might change with practice
- Super weak to Droll but it's not super common this format, could replace the Seventh package with Crossout targets

deck_excerpt: Time Thief X Horus - Rank 4 X Rank 8
deck_description:
Using the strenghts of the Horus and Armor XYZ engine, turn the Time Thief deck to a deck that can use the Rank 8 toolbox with ease, and unlock a few neat synergies. As well as finaly making Time Thief Temporwhal a core part of the strategy.

King's Sarcophagus combined with a lot of card that become useful once in the GY, and some retriavable cards (Full-Armored Xyz can be dumped twice, if you don't plan to use it's on field effect, by using Dark Knight Lancer's effect).

With King of the Feral Imps now being banned, our new main access to the Xyz Armor Fortress is Sakra Vendirage. Ideally we make it with a psychic monster as material, that we can detach with Winder so he can summon it back to give us an "early" Redoer. 

The equip effect of the Therion monsters can trigger Dark Knight Lancer.

And more...

- - - - - -

The ideal non interrupted bord would most of the time end on Dark Lancer, Therion "King" Regulus, Gigantic "Champion" Sargas, Silouhatte Rabbit, Redeor or Perpetua and both set Time Thief Power Reserve and Full Armored Xyz (to go into another Time Thief Xyz during the Standby phase), with idealy Time Thief Retrograde set as well.

Putting up a negate under 5 summon is quite easy thanks to the Horus engine with an early Photon lord, and most hands can go through a few interruptions.

- - - - - 

Things that could be changed righ now : Magicians' soul is really in to fix bad hands and put an Imsety in rotation if not available for some reasons.In a heavy handtrap format, i would swith it for your handtraps of choice. Once on the field i can only by used as link material. For that reason I could see siding in a Relinquished Anima. 

The Zombie Vampire, even if it's a bit risky, can fix youself both by giving you a look at your opponent deck and sending to your GY some of the missing Horus or Time Thief monsters you could need in rotation.

Game 2 going 2nd I would side out the field spells, Terraforming, and one of the Time thief trap. Side deck cards depicted here are personnal choices based on my local opponents usual decks, and could be switched for anything.

A budget friendly upgrade to the Crystal Beasts structure deck for an asping 12-year-old Yu-Gi-Oh player.

Tistina and Allure queen are a surprising combination.

 

Allong with the needed boost of Miasma dragon tistina, Chaos Allure Queen give more ways to send it to the graveyard.

She’s a free Chaos Angel if unbothered, and by equiping a Tistina monster from the graveyard she become a light Tistina monster on the field. More so, if she’s equiped with Crystal God Tistina, she will allow Demigod to trigger it’s effect even if Crystal god isn’t in the monster zone.

 

The deck work quite well with That’s 10, doing numerous effects in one turn, allowing you to place and summons Signs or You’re finished ! Turn 1 for extra lvl10 for XYZ plays.

 

Ratio could be adjusted to slot in handtraps for a more meta build (I’d remove That’s 10 and the trap monsters)

This isn’t so much of an Icejade Prediction Princess V.2 as it is pretty much just an updated version of my previous Icejade Prediction Princess Deck with the new additions of cards like the new Orcust support, Enneacraft - Astay.PIXIEA, and more non-engine. The Deck’s combo is pretty much the same and the Level 9 monster the Deck focuses on, Icejade Creation Kingfisher, is actually much easier to get out compared to some of the previous Level 9’s I worked with like Predaplant Triphyoverutum or X X-Saber Gottoms (hint hint I got a new X-Saber Prediction Princess Deck on the horizon, also I have to separated the X's or else it counts as profanity for some reason). Kingfisher still doesn’t actually do anything MUCH in most cases in this Deck, but it could perhaps bounce a card when you go through your set-up combo going second I dunno.

The combo is pretty much the same save for the new inclusion of Galatea-I, the Orcust Automaton. You just need Girsu, the Orcust Mekk-Knight and Icejade Creation Kingfisher which you can also either search through Icejade Cradle or Summon from Deck with Icejade Manifestation. Let’s just say that you drew Kingfisher. Normal Summon Girsu and activate his effect to send World Legacy - “World Armor” from Deck to GY. Activate Girsu’s other effect to Special Summon a World Legacy Token to both player’s fields. Link your World Legacy Token into Galatea-I, the Orcust Automaton. This is more or less just to put her into rotation for your next turn. Link Galatea-I and Girsu into Lib the World Key Blademaster. Activate Lib’s effect to set World Legacy Succession from your Deck. Activate Succession to Special Summon World Armor from GY to Linkpoint. On Special Summon, World Armor adds World Legacy Monstrosity from Deck to hand. Link World Armor and Lib into Ib the World Chalice Priestess. DO NOT activate Lib’s effect in GY. Now, activate Kingfisher’s effect in hand to equip itself to Ib. Activate Kingfisher’s other effect targeting your opponent’s World Legacy Token (as it has 0 ATK which is less than the DEF of the Link Monster Ib as Link Monsters have no DEF which is basically 0 DEF) to Special Summon Kingfisher and bounce (or remove) the Token. Activate Monstrosity targeting Kingfisher to Special Summon Prediction Princess Bibliomuse and Enneacraft - Astay.PIXIEA from Deck. Xyz PIXIEA and Kingfisher into Mereologic Aggregator who activates on Xyz Summon to send Herald of the Arc Light from Extra Deck to GY. Herald triggers off of being sent to GY to search for Prediction Princess Tarotrei. Activate Aggregator’s other effect, targeting Herald in GY, detaching 1, and attaching Herald from GY to it. Link Aggregator and Ib into S:P Little Knight. Herald triggers after being sent to GY again to add Underworld Ritual of Prediction from Deck to hand. Activate Underworld Ritual to Ritual Summon Tarotrei by tributing Bibliomuse. Bibliomuse triggers off of being tributed and sent to the GY and Special Summons itself back face-down. Activate Tarotrei to flip Bibliomuse face-up, which then allows you to activate Bibliomuse’s Flip Effect which adds Prediction Princess Tarotreith and another Underworld Ritual from Deck to hand. Activate Underworld Ritual tributing Bibliomuse to Ritual Summon Tarotreith face-down. During your End Phase, Tarotrei activates to Special Summon PIXIEA from your GY face-down. During your opponent’s Standby Phase, you can banish Underworld Ritual from GY to Special Summon another Bibliomuse from Deck face-down and then you can chain the effect of Tarotrei on field to flip Tarotreith face-up. Tarotreith’s Flip Effect triggers to Special Summon Deus-X Krawler from your Deck face-down and then on a new chain, you can activate Tarotreith’s other effect to flip all 3 of Bibliomuse, PIXIEA, and Deus-X face-up. Bibliomuse’s Flip Effect activates to add a Prediction Princess monster and a Ritual Spell from Deck to hand, and while it is face-up on your field, your Ritual Monsters gain protection from being targeted or destroyed by your opponent’s card effects. PIXIEA prevents your opponent from targeting cards on the field or in either GY with card effects after it is flipped face-up. Deus-X negates all activated monster effects on your opponent’s field, and then you have S:P Little Knight for some interaction. And why did we put Galatea-I into rotation? On a following turn, we can banish Girsu from GY to Special Summon Galatea-I from GY and then you now have an Orcust Link Monster to help make Enlilgirsu, the Orcust Mekk-Knight. And after you use it effect to steal a monster your opponent controls, you can either Link it off to then send a card on field to GY or use it to Xyz Summon Dingirsu, the Orcust of the Evening Star who can also send a card on field to GY on Xyz Summon. 

For the Main Deck Monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, 1 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, and 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. Tarotrei can Quick Effect flip a monster on field face-up or face-down and she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or GY face-down during your End Phase. Tarotreith must either be Ritual Summoned or Special Summoned via Tarotrei's effect in the End Phase. Her Flip Effect Special Summons a Flip Monster from your Deck face-down and she can also Quick Effect flip any number of your monsters face-up or face-down. Bibliomuse can Special Summon herself back face-down after being Tributed and sent there. Her Flip Effect adds a Prediction Princess monster other than herself and a Ritual Spell from Deck to hand and while she is face-up on the field, your Ritual Monsters gain targeting and destruction protection from your opponent’s card effects. 1 Deus-X Krawler which negates all activated monster effects on your opponent's side of the field after it has been flipped face-up and if it is destroyed on field, you can search for a Level 9 monster with a different Type and Attribute. 1 Enneacraft - Astay.PIXIEA which can, when your opponent activates a card or effect that targets a card(s) you control, flip itself face-up as part of this effect’s activation in order to negate that effect and then allow you to banish a random card out of your opponent’s hand face-down. Also, after it has been flipped face-up, your opponent cannot target cards on either field or in either GY with card effects. If you want to play this Deck immediately TCG legal at the time of posting this, you can play Pot of the Forbidden instead. 2 Icejade Creation Kingfisher which can target a WATER monster you control to equip itself from hand to that monster. And while it is equipped to a monster, you can target 1 monster your opponent controls with ATK less than or equal to the equipped monster’s DEF and then Special Summon Kingfisher and bounce that monster to the hand. 1 World Legacy - “World Armor” which can add a World Legacy card from Deck to hand when it is Normal or Special Summoned. 1 World Legacy - “World Wand” which you can banish from GY and target a banished Orcust monster to Special Summon that monster, but you are locked into DARK monsters for the rest of the turn. If you do not draw Kingfisher, you can use Galatea-I’s effect on field to send a card from your hand to GY to add World Wand from Deck to hand. In that case, after you make Lib and Special Summon back World Armor to search for Monstrosity, you can banish Girsu from GY to Special Summon back Galatea-I. And with 3 monsters with different names, you can banish all 3 of them for Trishula, the Dragon of Icy Imprisonment which can act as your Level 9 on field to target with Monstrosity. In that case, on a following turn, you can Link Summon Barricadeborg Blocker to discard World Wand and then use World Wand to bring back Galatea-I from banishment and then do the whole Enlilgirsu thing that I mentioned earlier. 3 Girsu, the Orcust Mekk-Knight which sends an Orcust or World Legacy card from Deck to GY on Normal or Special Summon. Also, if it is the only monster you control, you can Special Summon a World Legacy Token to both player’s fields. 3 Mulcharmy Fuwalos, 3 Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring, and 3 Droll & Lock Bird. 

For Spell/Traps: 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which can Ritual Summon a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand or GY face-up or face-down and you can banish it from GY during the Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess monster from Deck face-down. 3 Icejade Cradle which adds an Icejade monster with a different name than the cards you control or in your GY. 2 Icejade Manifestation which can take an Icejade monster from your Deck and either Special Summon it or send it to GY if you control a WATER monster and  your opponent has a monster on their field or in their GY. 1 Pot of Prosperity. 3 Small World. 1 World Legacy Monstrosity which can either Special Summon a Level 9 monster from your hand or target a Level 9 monster you control to Special Summon 2 Level 9 monsters from your Deck with a different type and Attribute, but with different names. 1 World Legacy Succession which targets and Special Summons a monster from your GY to Linkpoint. 3 Infinite Impermanence. 

Extra Deck: 1 Trishula, the Dragon of Icy Imprisonment. If you don’t have access to Kingfisher, but you still have access to Girsu, you can make Trishula instead and still do full Prediction Princess combo. 1 Herald of the Arc Light which adds a Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell from Deck to hand if it is sent to GY. 1 Super Starslayer TY-PHON - Sky Crisis. 2 Mereologic Aggregator. 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity. 1 Dingirsu, the Orcust of the Evening Star which on Xyz Summon can either send a card on field to GY to attach a banished Machine monster it itself. Also, if a card(s) you control would be destroyed by battle or card effect, you can detach a material from it instead. You can also Xyz Summon it by using an Orcust Link Monster you control as material. 1 Enlilgirsu, the Orcust Mekk-Knight which requires 2+ monsters including an Orcust Link Monster. He can target a banished Orcust or World Legacy card and add it to your hand and then you can shuffle a card from your hand into the Deck to take control of a face-up monster your opponent controls. Also, during the Main Phase, if it is in the GY because it was sent from the EMZ to the GY this turn, you can banish it from GY to send a card on field to GY. 1 S:P Little Knight. 1 Barricadeborg Blocker which can just facilitate a discard. 1 Lib the World Key Blademaster who can only be Link Summoned while you have a World Legacy card in your GY. She can set a World Legacy Spell/Trap from Deck, but it cannot be activated this turn unless you have a World Legacy monster in your GY and if it is sent to GY because it was used as Link Material, you can shuffle a card on field into the Deck. 1 Ib the World Chalice Priestess which is just a LINK-2 WATER we can make for our purposes. 1 Galatea-I, the Orcust Automaton which  cannot be used as Xyz Material and can only be Link Summoned once per turn. She can send a card from your hand to the GY to add either Orcustrated Babel or a World Legacy monster from Deck to hand and if it is in your GY, you can banish another Orcust monster from your GY to Special Summon her from GY. 1 Gravity Controller. 

Side Deck: Nibiru, the Primal Being, 2 Mulcharmy Purulia, 3 Effect Veiler, 1 Triple Tactics Talent, 2 Lightningstorm, 1 Harpie’s Feather Duster, and 3 Evenly Matched.

deck_description:
Category: Tournament Meta Decks (TCG)

Tournament Meta Decks are current-level Meta Decks that are capable of going up against the best of the best. These are curated lists that cannot be uploaded by regular users.

Creator: Atos Alves do Nascimento

Tournament: Caruaru WCQ Regional – September 14th 2025

Placement: Top 8

Pretend the copies of Ipt al Hecahands are copies of Hecahands. I'll fix it when it's added to the card database.

Hecahands is not a bad archetype, nor is it a bad Deck. In fact, I think it makes for a very solid deck. Hecahands, Hecahands Yadel, Hecahands Ibel, and Hecahands Jawza are all really great cards for the Deck that provide a great degree of consistency, ensuring that you are able to end on their main sources of interruption in Yad al Hecahands and Ipt al Hecahands with some number of their Level 7 monsters in rotation to take your opponent’s monsters, depriving them of such resources at key points, and you also have the possibility of also ending on Hecahands Tartarus to go into Hecahands Xeno to then take your opponent’s monsters right out of their Extra Deck for your own purposes.

It just so happens that Hecahands has a Level 9 monster in Hecahands Xeno. It is a Level 9 DARK Illusion Fusion Monster who requires 3 Hecahands monsters as Fusion Material. Other than the standard Illusion monster effect of it and monsters it battles not being able to be destroyed by battle, Xeno can also, during the Main Phase, Quick Effect look at 2 random face-down cards in your opponent’s Extra Deck and then you can Special Summon 1 of those monsters to your field. And if it is Fusion Summoned and destroyed by your opponent’s card effect while in your control, you can take control of any number of monsters your opponent controls. Xeno is a really good card for getting key cards out of your opponent’s Extra Deck, similar to Kashtira Unicorn. The difference is that Unicorn can choose any card in your opponent’s Extra Deck while Xeno has to choose between 2 random cards. But, if you hit a key 1-of, it still does the damage. But, I don’t think anyone is dumb enough to destroy Xeno by card effect while they have a full board and no ways to negate Xeno’s on-destruction effect to take control of any number of your opponent’s monsters. The issue that I have with Hecahands when it comes to including it in Prediction Princess is that you can use another archetype as an engine to facilitate your Hecahands plays, but you can’t really use Hecahands as an engine to facilitate another Deck’s plays, especially not Prediction Princess plays. And it really does not help with the fact that making Xeno turn 1 is almost as much of a chore as it is to make Mikanko Prediction Princess work. Most of the Hecahands cards require your opponent to make a few contributions in order for you to pinpoint your interactions and steal their cards for your own use, and this usually happens when you go second or when you do your Turn 1 and pass over to your opponent for them to have their first turn. Sure, you have some proactive cards like Hecahands Gygas and Hecahands Breus, but both have the chance to miss taking a monster from your opponent with Breus having a somewhat lesser chance of hitting than Gygas in my opinion. What I am trying to say is that Xeno is not a card you make on Turn 1 of the Duel. You are making it on your opponent’s turn or when you go second at the very least. But because it is the Level 9 we are focusing on in this Deck, we have to rely on a pretty unorthodox combo to get where we need to go.

For this Deck’s combo, you need Nightmare Apprentice, any Hecahands monster, and World Legacy Monstrosity. Not what you like to see, but it’s what we gotta do to make this work. Let’s say that the Hecahands monster you have in hand is Hecahands Yadel. Discard Yadel to Special Summon Nightmare Apprentice from hand. On Special Summon, Nightmare Apprentice searches for Hecahands Ibel from Deck. Activate Ibel in hand, shuffling it back into the Deck, and Special Summoning Hecahands Gygas from Deck. Activate Gygas’s effect to excavate the top 3 cards of your opponent’s Deck and Special Summoning 1 excavated monster to your field, shuffling the rest back into the Deck. Tribute Apprentice and the monster you stole to Special Summon Hecahands Jawza from Extra Deck. Activate Jawza’s effect to add Hecahands Tartarus from Deck to hand. Activate Tartarus to Fusion Summon Hecahands Xeno from Extra Deck by banishing Yadel from GY and Gygas and Jawza you control. Activate Monstrosity targeting Xeno to Special Summon Prediction Princess Bibliomuse and Enneacraft - Astay.PIXIEA from Deck. Activate Xeno’s effect to look at 2 random face-down cards in your opponent’s Extra Deck and Special Summon one of those monsters to your field. Xyz PIXIEA and Xeno into Mereologic Aggregator in the EMZ. On Xyz Summon, Aggregator activates to send Herald of the Arc Light from Extra Deck to GY which triggers it to search for Prediction Princess Tarotrei. Aggregator activates its other effect targeting Herald in GY, detaching 1, and attaching Herald back from GY. Link Aggregator and the monster you Special Summoned from your opponent’s Extra Deck into I:P Masquerena or S:P Little Knight (if the monster Summoned happens to be a Link Monster).  Herald triggers after being sent to GY again to search for Underworld Ritual of Prediction. Activate Underworld Ritual to Ritual Summon Tarotrei by tributing Bibliomuse. Bibliomuse triggers in GY off of being tributed and Special Summons herself back from GY face-down. Activate Tarotrei to flip Bibliomuse face-up. Bibliomuse’s Flip Effect searches for Prediction Princess Tarotreith and another Underworld Ritual. Activate Underworld Ritual tributing Bibliomuse to Ritual Summon Tarotreith face-down. During the End Phase, Tarotrei Special Summons PIXIEA from GY face-down. During your opponent’s Standby Phase, you can banish Underworld Ritual from GY to Special Summon a Bibliomuse from Deck face-down and then Tarotrei can flip Tarotreith face-up. Tarotreith’s Flip Effect Special Summons Deus-X Krawler from Deck and then you can use its other effect to flip Bibiomuse, Deus-X, and PIXIEA face-up. You now have S:P or I:P who can go into S:P, Bibliomuse’s Flip Effect searches for another Prediction Princess monster and a Ritual Spell and protects your Ritual Monsters from targeting and destruction, PIXIEA prevents your opponent from targeting cards on field or in GY with card effects, Deus-X negates the activated monster effects on your opponent’s side of the field, and you ripped a card out of your opponent’s Extra Deck earlier.

For the Main Deck Monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, 1 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, and 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. Tarotrei can Quick Effect flip a monster on field face-up or face-down and she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or GY face-down during your End Phase. Tarotreith must either be Ritual Summoned or Special Summoned via Tarotrei's effect in the End Phase. Her Flip Effect Special Summons a Flip Monster from your Deck face-down and she can also Quick Effect flip any number of your monsters face-up or face-down. Bibliomuse can Special Summon herself back face-down after being Tributed and sent there. Her Flip Effect adds a Prediction Princess monster other than herself and a Ritual Spell from Deck to hand and while she is face-up on the field, your Ritual Monsters gain targeting and destruction protection from your opponent’s card effects. 1 Deus-X Krawler which negates all activated monster effects on your opponent's side of the field after it has been flipped face-up and if it is destroyed on field, you can search for a Level 9 monster with a different Type and Attribute. 1 Enneacraft - Astay.PIXIEA which can, when your opponent activates a card or effect that targets a card(s) you control, flip itself face-up as part of this effect’s activation in order to negate that effect and then allow you to banish a random card out of your opponent’s hand face-down. Also, after it has been flipped face-up, your opponent cannot target cards on either field or in either GY with card effects. For the Hecahands monsters: 1 Hecahands Gygas, 1 Hecahands Breus, 3 Hecahands Ibel, and 3 Hecahands Yadel. I’m just going to be listing their effects that we are actually using in this Deck. Gygas can excavate the top 3 cards of your opponent’s Deck and can Special Summon an excavated monster to your field, shuffling the rest back into the Deck. On the other hand, Breus looks at a random card in your opponent’s hand and can Special Summon it to your field if it is a monster. Both Gygas and Breus force you to gamble, so I don’t really feel like arguing for one over the other. Ibel and Yadel both activate in hand and shuffle themselves back into the Deck to either Special Summon a Hecahands monster from Deck in the case of Ibel or search for a Hecahands Spell/Trap in the case of Yadel. 3 Nightmare Apprentice which can discard a card to Special Summon itself from hand. Very good. And she can also add an Illusion Monster from Deck to hand on Normal or Special Summon. Extremely good. Finally, 3 Spirit Sculptor. It can tribute a monster to add a monster from Deck whose combined original ATK/DEF equals the tributed monster’s combined ATK/DEF. I got this idea from watching El Exordio del Duelista (love this guy). Essentially, you are using Sculptor to tribute itself and since it has 1600 ATK and 2100 DEF, you can search for a monster with 3700 combined ATK/DEF, and it just so happens that Ibel, Yadel, and Nightmare Apprentice all have a combined ATK/DEF of 3700.

For Spell/Traps, we have 3 Hecahands and 1 Hecahands Tartarus. Hecahands just adds a Hecahands monster from Deck to hand. No need to send 1 other card you control to GY on activation to also set a Hecahands Spell/Trap from Deck since we can’t really make use of a second Tartarus or either of the Counter Traps. It’s GY effect is not used in this Deck, but I do really wish that it was the same as Dark World Dealings just to feel less bad about using this effect in a regular Hecahands Deck. Tartarus allows you to either target and bounce a Spell/Trap your opponent controls to hand while you control a Hecahands monster or Fusion Summon a Hecahands Fusion Monster by banishing materials from field and/or GY which also treats monsters owned by your opponent that you stole as Hecahands monsters. You only need the 1 copy. 3 World Legacy Monstrosity which can either Special Summon a Level 9 monster from your hand or target a Level 9 monster you control to Special Summon 2 Level 9 monsters from your Deck with a different type and Attribute, but with different names. 1 Instant Fusion for Master of Ham. 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which can Ritual Summon a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand or GY face-up or face-down and you can banish it from GY during the Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess monster from Deck face-down. 2 Prediction Ritual which specially only can be used to Ritual Summon Prediction Princess Tarotrei and you can banish it from GY except the turn it was sent there to search a Prediction Princess monster. 3 Pre-Preparation of Rites which searches a Ritual Spell from Deck and a Ritual Monster that is mentioned on that Ritual Spell from your Deck or GY. Finally, the 1 Called by the Grave. 

Extra Deck: 1 Hecahands Xeno. 2 Hecahands Jawza. Jawza needs a Hecahands monster and an Illusion Monster as material, but you can also Special Summon it from Extra Deck by Tributing an Illusion Monster and a monster owned by your opponent that you stole. Other big thing that it does is add a Hecahands card from Deck or GY to hand. 1 Master of Ham which can on Fusion Summon can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or Deck face-down. 1 Elder Entity N’tss which can target and destroy a card on field if it is sent to GY. 1 Herald of the Arc Light which, if sent to GY, can search for either a Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell from Deck. 1 Super Starslayer TY-PHON - Sky Crisis. 1 Infinitrack Earth Slicer. 2 Mereologic Aggregator, 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows, and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity. 1 Nine-Lives Cat it can detach a material to target either a Level 9 monster in your GY or a monster in your opponent’s GY and Special Summon it. What you can do with Nine-Lives Cat is target Xeno in your GY, bring it back, and then use its effect to look at another 2 random cards in your opponent’s Extra Deck and Special Summon 1 of those monsters. And then you can Tribute them for Jawza and search for a Hecahands card like Ibel to get like Breus to potentially yoink a monster out of your opponent’’s hand or something. 1 S:P Little Knight, 1 I:P Masquerena, and 1 Gravity Controller. Gravity Controller is really only here in case you whiff off of Xeno’s effect like if you reveal 2 monsters that must be Fusion Summoned or must first be Xyz Summoned or something. 

Side Deck: 3 Nibiru, the Primal Being, 3 Droll & Lock Bird, 1 Illusion Gate, 1 Change of Heart, 2 Triple Tactics Thrust, 1 Triple Tactics Talent, and 3 Evenly Matched.

When Yugi Muto won the Domino High Tourney he would’ve been provided a tour of Maximillion Pegasus’ card factory but declined due to a family trip to Egypt. While on the trip, another tournament was waged for all of Domino City as a prelude to another, currently unannounced, Tournament. Tristan failed to impress Ribbon during the Domino High Tourney and unlike another classmate, has accepted that they’ll stay friends. He’s excited to duel after updating his deck.

My previous Gold Pride Prediction Princess Deck definitely had the right idea of where to go with the Deck, but the other cards that I considered for the Deck were not the most optimal. Predaplant Ophrys Scorpio and Predaplant Darlingtonia Cobra are so incredibly helpful for both searching for a Fusion Spell as well as for essentially putting 2 Level 3 bodies on the field to go into Gold Pride - Chariot Carrie who can then transition to the necessary Gold Pride plays in this Deck. The only “issue” with my previous list, if you can really call it one, was that the only Fusion Spell in the Deck for Cobra to search was Instant Fusion to then Special Summon Master of Ham. But, I had completely forgotten about Overload Fusion which could help us Fusion Summon 2 copies of Gold Pride’s only Level 9 monster, Gold Pride - Pin Baller, and with 2 Level 9’s, we can go into Mereologic Aggregator and transition to full Prediction Princess combo. However, instead of Overload Fusion, I am going to instead play Over Future Fusion in this Deck because it is essentially just Overload Fusion with some added benefits. If you want to make this Deck TCG legal, since Over Future Fusion is not out yet, you can play Overload Fusion instead, but I would definitely recommend playing Over Future Fusion when it does release in the TCG. 

Full combo is Predaplant Ophrys Scorpio, a Prediction Princess card, and a monster to send to GY as cost for Scorpio’s effect. Naturally, if the Prediction Princess card you open is a Ritual monster, it can both fulfill the Prediction Princess card requirement and be sent to GY as cost for Scorpio’s effect. If you draw a Ritual Spell or Prediction Princess Bibliomuse, you are going to need a different monster to send to GY for cost. Let’s just say that the Prediction Princess card you open is Prediction Princess Tarotrei. Normal Summon Scorpio and activate its effect, sending Tarotrei from hand to GY as cost, to Special Summon Predaplant Darlingtonia Cobra from Deck. Since Cobra was Special Summoned by the effect of a Predaplant monster, it can search for Over Future Fusion from Deck. Xyz Cobra and Scorpio into Gold Pride - Chariot Carrie. Activate Carrie’s effect, detaching 1 Xyz Material to add Gold Pride - Better Luck Next Time! from Deck to hand. Activate Better Luck Next Time and use its effect on activation to add Gold Pride - Roller Baller from Deck to hand, losing LP equal to its ATK. Because your LP are now lower than your opponent’s, you can Special Summon Roller Baller from hand and then you can use its other effect to Fusion Summon a Gold Pride Fusion Monster. Fuse Chariot Carrie and Roller Baller into Gold Pride - Pin Baller. Activate Over Future Fusion and activate its second effect which allows you to Fusion Summon a DARK Machine Fusion Monster from your Extra Deck by banishing Fusion Material monster from your GY. Banish Chariot Carrie and Roller Baller to Fusion Summon another Pin Baller. Xyz the 2 Pin Ballers into Mereologic Aggregator in the EMZ. On Xyz Summon, Aggregator sends Herald of the Arc Light from Extra Deck to GY. Herald triggers off of being sent to GY and searches for Prediction Princess Tarotreith. Activate Aggregator’s other effect to target Herald in GY, detach 1 material, and attach Herald from GY to it. Link Aggregator into Gravity Controller and then Herald triggers off of being sent to GY again and searches for Underworld Ritual of Prediction. Activate Underworld Ritual to Ritual Summon Tarotrei by tributing Tarotreith. During the End Phase, Tarotrei Special Summons Tarotreith from GY face-down. During your opponent’s Standby Phase, banish Underworld Ritual from GY to Special Summon Prediction Princess Bibliomuse from Deck face-down and chain the effect of Prediction Princess Tarotrei to flip Tarotreith face-up. Tarotreith’s Flip Effect activates to Special Summon Deus-X Krawler from Deck face-down. On a new chain, Tarotreith can Quick Effect flip both Bibliomuse and Deus-X face-up. Bibliomuse’s Flip Effect activates to search for another Prediction Princess monster and a Ritual Spell and while she is face-up on the field, your Ritual Monsters gain targeting and destruction protection from your opponent’s card effects. And then you have Deus-X who negates all activated monster effects on your opponent’s field. That’s like a decent board to end on, but remember that you still have Over Future Fusion on field. During your next turn, you can activate its first effect to reveal your third copy of Pin Baller in Extra Deck to send another copy of Roller Baller from Deck to GY. Then, you can use Over Future Fusion’s second effect to Fusion Summon said Pin Baller by banishing the sent Roller Baller and up to both Pin Ballers in GY. If your opponent has any face-up monsters when you do this, Pin Baller can equip up to 3 monsters your opponent controls to itself. Can’t do this if you are playing Overload Fusion, but you will be able to as soon as we get Over Future Fusion. 

For the Main Deck Monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, 2 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, and 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. Tarotrei can Quick Effect flip a monster on field face-up or face-down and she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or GY face-down during your End Phase. Tarotreith must either be Ritual Summoned or Special Summoned via Tarotrei's effect in the End Phase. Her Flip Effect Special Summons a Flip Monster from your Deck face-down and she can also Quick Effect flip any number of your monsters face-up or face-down. Bibliomuse can Special Summon herself back face-down after being Tributed and sent there. Her Flip Effect adds a Prediction Princess monster other than herself and a Ritual Spell from Deck to hand and while she is face-up on the field, your Ritual Monsters gain targeting and destruction protection from your opponent’s card effects. 1 Deus-X Krawler which negates all activated monster effects on your opponent's side of the field after it has been flipped face-up and if it is destroyed on field, you can search for a Level 9 monster with a different Type and Attribute. 2 Gold Pride - Roller Baller which can Special Summon itself from hand while your LP are lower than your opponent’s. Also, it can Quick Effect Fusion Summon a Gold Pride Fusion Monster from your Extra Deck using monsters from your hand or field during the Main Phase. 1 Whirlwind Weasel whose Flip Effect prevents your opponent from activating Spell/Trap Cards for the rest of the turn. Again, you can choose to play a second copy of Deus-X or a Guard Dog in place of this card if you want. 3 Predaplant Ophrys Scorpio and 1 Predaplant Darlingtonia Cobra. Scorpio can send a monster from hand to GY on Normal or Special Summon to Special Summon a Predaplant from Deck. If Cobra is Special Summoned by a Predaplant monster’s effect, it can add a Fusion or Polymerization Spell Card from your Deck to your hand once per Duel. 3 Lonefire Blossom which can tribute a Plant to Special Summon a Plant from Deck. 3 Mulcharmy Fuwalos, 3 Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring, and 3 Droll & Lock Bird.

For Spell/Traps: 1 Pot of Prosperity. 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which can Ritual Summon a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand or GY face-up or face-down and you can banish it from GY during the Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess monster from Deck face-down. 1 Instant Fusion for either Master of Ham or Predaplant Ambulomelides who can search Scorpio to get your combo going. Or, it can add Scorpio on Fusion Summon and then Tribute itself to Special Summon Scorpio from Deck to give you both a Scorpio and a monster to send for Scorpio’s effect. 3 Small World. 1 Gold Pride - Better Luck Next Time!. It is a Continuous Spell that adds a Gold Pride from Deck to hand on activation but you lose LP equal to that monster’s ATK. That’s pretty much all that we are using it for. It is important that you search Roller Baller through this card because Better Luck Next Time is the card that you are using to reduce your LP to make them lower than your opponent’s in order to be able to Special Summon Roller Baller from hand. 1 Over Future Fusion. It’s a Continuous Spell with 2 effects that are both once per turn only. The first effect has you reveal a Fusion Monster in your Extra Deck and send 1 Fusion Material mentioned on it by name from your Deck to GY, but you cannot Special Summon monsters or activate monster effects with that name for the rest of the turn. The second effect allows you to Fusion Summon a DARK Machine Fusion Monster from your Extra Deck by banishing Fusion Materials from your GY. Very cool card. And finally, 3 Infinite Impermanence. 

Extra Deck: 3 Gold Pride - Pin Baller. It is a Level 9 DARK Machine Fusion Monster that requires Gold Pride - Roller Baller and 1+ Gold Pride monsters as material. On Fusion Summon, you can equip face-up monsters your opponent controls to it up to the number of Fusion Materials used for its Summon, and you can actually utilize this effect in this Deck thanks to Over Future Fusion. Notably, this effect’s activation and effect cannot be negated if your LP are lower than your opponent’s. During the End Phase in which it used this effect this turn, you must return it to the Extra Deck and then Special Summon Roller Baller from your Deck or GY, which I doubt you are going to get to this point in Prediction Princess. Y’know, stall out your opponent’s turn with Deus-X, Whirlwind Weasel, or Guard Dog, pass over to your turn where you can Over Future Fusion into the third Pin Baller to scoop up any monsters your opponent may have put on the field, and then because most of your monsters are really big, you can just go for game there. Also, 3 copies of Pin Baller which is really important if you want to make full use of Over Future Fusion: 2 for your set-up and the 3rd for follow-up. 1 Predaplant Ambulomelides which on Fusion Summon adds a Predap card from Deck to hand and you can target a monster you control or an opponent’s monster that has a Predator Counter and tribute that monster to Special Summon a Predaplant from Deck. Again, if you draw Instant Fusion, you can choose to Summon Ambulomelides. On Fusion Summon, you can search for a Scorpio and then use its other effect, tributing itself to Special Summon another Scorpio from Deck. That way, the Scorpio you Special Summoned can use its effect and send the Scorpio you added to hand to GY as cost. 1 Master of Ham who can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or Deck face-down on Fusion Summon. 1 Elder Entity N’tss which, I realized I never really explained, so I’ll do it here. The banlist limiting Herald does not affect us because we only ever go through the one copy of Herald in our set-up combos, but I usually play 2 because why not. Because N’tss can target and destroy a card on field when it is sent to GY, which is not a once per turn, you can make another Aggregator on a following turn, use its effect on Xyz Summon to send N’tss to pop a card, activate its other effect to attach N’tss back from GY to itself, and then Link off Aggregator to pop another card and then negate the effects of a different card on field with Aggregator’s GY effect. Speaking of, 1 Herald of the Arc Light which adds a Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell from Deck to hand if it is sent to the GY. 1 Super Starslayer TY-PHON - Sky Crisis. 2 Mereologic Aggregator. 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity. 1 Gold Pride - Chariot Carrie who is a Rank 3 Xyz that can detach a material to add a Gold Pride Spell/Trap from Deck to hand. All you really need to use her for, and she’s real important since she grabs you Better Luck Next Time. 1 S:P Little Knight and 1 Gravity Controller.

Side Deck: 2 Nibiru, the Primal Being, 3 Mulcharmy Purulia, 2 Ghost Belle & Haunted Mansion, 3 Lightning Storm, 1 Triple Tactics Talent, 3 Evenly Matched, and 1 Solemn Judgment. A note about Judgment. The reason why I included it in the Side Decks of both my Predaplant Prediction Princess list and my Insect Prediction Princess list is because I just felt like Judgment got a whole lot better in the current format, especially when you are Judgmenting a Dracotail Fusion Spell, which is a Deck that can absolutely play around Deus-X if you didn’t realize. Limiting Judgment doesn’t hurt Prediction Princess, but I would only play it at 1 if I am feeling cute or if I am also playing like some number of other Solemn Traps. Anti-Spell Fragrance is also good and if you need to clear it on your following turn, you can make Aggregator and send N’tss to pop it or you can Link off said Aggregator to negate the effects of Anti-Spell until the end of the turn and still have it for your opponent’s next turn if you didn’t kill them yet.

I actually wasn’t planning to make this Deck. I was trying to make either True Draco Prediction Princess or True King Prediction Princess work using their new support, and because my previous lists for both of those Decks used Deep Sea Diva, I got carried away with trying to transition from Normal Summoning Diva to full Prediction Princess combo. Surprisingly, Diva by herself does amount to full Prediction Princess combo. But, things can get real wacky in this Deck. There are 2 starting hands that this Deck can utilize for full combo, albeit different combos, but both are still full combo. 

This first combo is just Deep Sea Diva and a discard. Normal Summon Diva and activate her effect on Normal Summon to Special Summon Neptabyss, the Atlantean Prince from Deck. Activate Neptabyss’s effect on field, sending Atlantean Dragoons from Deck to GY for cost, in order to add Poseidra, the Storming Atlantean from Deck to hand. Dragoons triggers in GY as it was sent to GY to activate a WATER monster’s effect which allows you to add another copy of Neptabyss from Deck to hand. Poseidra activates in hand, sending Neptabyss from hand to GY, in order to Special Summon itself from hand. Neptabyss triggers in GY after being sent there to activate a WATER monster’s effect and targets and Special Summons Dragoons back from GY. Synchro Diva and Neptabyss into THE Star Ham. On Synchro Summon, THE Star Ham discards a card to Special Summon Diva back from GY. Synchro Diva and Star Ham into Ib the World Chalice Justiciar who adds World Legacy Monstrosity from Deck to hand on Synchro Summon. Synchro Ib and Dragoons into Ravenous Crocodragon Archethys. On Synchro Summon, Archethys draws you a card. Activate Monstrosity targeting Archethys in order to Special Summon Prediction Princess Bibliomuse and Enneacraft - Astay.PIXIEA from Deck. Xyz PIXIEA and Archethys into Mereologic Aggregator who sends Herald of the Arc Light from Extra Deck to GY on Xyz Summon. Herald triggers off of being sent to GY and adds Prediction Princess Tarotrei from Deck to hand. Activate Aggregator’s other effect targeting Herald in GY, detaching 1 material, and attaching Herald from GY to itself. Link Aggregator and Poseidra into I:P Masquerena. Herald triggers off of being sent to GY again and adds Underworld Ritual of Prediction from Deck to hand. Activate Underworld Ritual to Ritual Summon Tarotrei by tributing Bibliomuse. Bibliomuse activates in GY off of being tributed and Special Summons herself back face-down. Activate Tarotrei’s effect to flip Bibliomuse face-up, and then Bibliomuse’s Flip Effect activates to add Prediction Princess Tarotreith and another Underworld Ritual from Deck to hand. Activate Underworld Ritual to Ritual Summon Tarotreith face-down by tributing Bibliomuse. During the End Phase, Tarotrei can Special Summon PIXIEA back from GY face-down. During your opponent’s Standby Phase, you can banish Underworld Ritual from GY to Special Summon another Bibliomuse from Deck and then chain Tarotrei’s effect to flip Tarotreith face-up. Tarotreith’s Flip Effect activates to Special Summon Deus-X Krawler from Deck, and then on a new chain, you can activate Tarotreith’s other effect to flip Bibliomuse, PIXIEA, and Deus-X face-up. Bibliomuse’s Flip Effect adds a Prediction Princess monster and another Underworld Ritual from Deck to hand and while she is face-up on the field, your Ritual Monsters gain targeting and destruction protection from your opponent’s card effects. PIXIEA, after it is flipped face-up, prevents your opponent from targeting cards on either field or in either GY with card effects. Deus-X negates all activated monster effects on your opponent’s field, and then you also have I:P who can go into S:P Little Knight for additional interaction. 

And now for the wacky combo, it requires you to open Mermail Abyssteus, Atlantean Dragoons, and a discard. Activate Abyssteus in hands, discarding Dragoons, to Special Summon itself from hand. As much I would like to then add either Abyssrhine, the Atlantean Spirit or Mermail Shadow Squad with Abyssteus’s effect, we aren’t playing them because their best effect locks you into WATER monsters from the Extra Deck for the rest of the turn. Either way, going back to the combo, Dragoons triggers in GY as it was sent to GY to activate a WATER monster’s effect, so it adds you Deep Sea Diva from Deck to hand. Normal Summon Diva and use her effect on Normal Summon to Special Summon Neptabyss, the Atlantean Prince from Deck. Activate Neptabyss’s effect on field, sending Atlantean Dragoons from Deck to GY for cost, in order to add Poseidra, the Storming Atlantean from Deck to hand. Dragoons triggers in GY as it was sent to GY to activate a WATER monster’s effect which allows you to add another copy of Neptabyss from Deck to hand. Poseidra activates in hand, sending Neptabyss from hand to GY, in order to Special Summon itself from hand. Neptabyss triggers in GY after being sent there to activate a WATER monster’s effect and targets and Special Summons Dragoons back from GY. Synchro Diva and Neptabyss into THE Star Ham. On Synchro Summon, THE Star Ham discards a card to Special Summon Diva back from GY. Synchro Diva and Star Ham into Ib the World Chalice Justiciar who adds World Legacy Monstrosity from Deck to hand on Synchro Summon. Synchro Ib and Dragoons into Ravenous Crocodragon Archethys. On Synchro Summon, Archethys draws you a card. Now, because you have the Level 7 Abyssteus and the Level 7 Poseidra, the Storming Atlantean on field, you can Xyz Summon Abysstrite, the Atlantean Spirit using them. On Xyz Summon, Abysstrite targets and Special Summons Dragoons back from GY. Then, you can Xyz Summon Poseidra Abyss, the Atlantean Dragon Lord by using Abysstrite as Xyz Material. Activate Monstrosity targeting Archethys to Special Summon Prediction Princess Bibliomuse and Deus-X Krawler from Deck. Xyz Deus-X and Archethys into Mereologic Aggregator who sends Herald of the Arc Light from Extra Deck to GY on Xyz Summon. Herald triggers off of being sent to GY and adds Prediction Princess Tarotrei from Deck to hand. Activate Aggregator’s other effect targeting Herald in GY, detaching 1 material, and attaching Herald from GY to itself. Link Poseidra Abyss and Aggregator into I:P Masquerena. Chain Link 1 Herald in GY and Chain Link 2 Poseidra Abyss in GY discarding a card. On resolution, Poseidra Abyss Special Summons Diva and 2 copies of Neptabyss from GY and Herald searches for a copy of Underworld Ritual of Prediction. With Masquerena, Diva, 2 copies of Neptabyss, and Dragoons on field, you have enough material to make a LINK-6 monster, so Link them all off into Firewall Dragon Singularity. Activate Underworld Ritual to Ritual Summon Tarotrei by tributing Bibliomuse. Bibliomuse activates in GY off of being tributed and Special Summons herself back face-down to the Main Monster Zone below Singularity (your MMZ that it points to). Activate Tarotrei’s effect to flip Bibliomuse face-up, and then Bibliomuse’s Flip Effect activates to add Prediction Princess Tarotreith and another Underworld Ritual from Deck to hand. Activate Underworld Ritual to Ritual Summon Tarotreith face-down by tributing Bibliomuse. Because a monster Singularity points to was sent to the GY, it can target a Cyberse monster in your GY and Special Summon it. Special Summon Masquerena back to the field. During the End Phase, Tarotrei can Special Summon Deus-X back from GY face-down. During your opponent’s Standby Phase, because you only have 1 available MMZ left, you can choose to either banish Underworld Ritual from GY to Special Summon a Bibliomuse from Deck face-down and later flip it face-up with Tarotreith to search for a Prediction Princess monster and a Ritual Spell while it also being able to provide your Ritual Monsters with targeting and destruction protection from your opponent’s card effects or you can instead activate Tarotrei’s effect to flip Tarotreith face-up and use her Flip Effect to Special Summon Enneacraft - Astay.PIXIEA from Deck and then on a new chain, you can Tarotreith to flip both Deus-X and PIXIEA face-up. Deus-X negates all activated monster effects on your opponent’s side of the field and PIXIEA prevents your opponent from targeting cards on either field or in either GY with card effects after it has been flipped face-up. Whichever, you choose to do, you also still have a Firewall Dragon Singularity that cannot be destroyed by your opponent’s card effects who can Quick Effect target up to 3 cards your opponent controls or in their GY and return them to the hand as you have Ritual, Synchro, and Xyz Monsters on field and/or in GY. Also, you have Masquerena who can Quick Effect perform a Link Summon into either S:P Little Knight or Dyna Mondo for more interruption. Also, say you Link off a monster that Singularity was pointing to with I:P’s Quick Effect Link Summon, so you could also then Special Summon a Cyberse back from your GY with Singularity’s effect, which can be either Masquerena again to use her for Link Material next turn to make something indestructible by card effects or you can bring back Aggregator which targets a card on field and negates its effects until the end of the turn if it is sent to GY.

For the Main Deck Monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, 1 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, and 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. Tarotrei can Quick Effect flip a monster on field face-up or face-down and she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or GY face-down during your End Phase. Tarotreith must either be Ritual Summoned or Special Summoned via Tarotrei's effect in the End Phase. Her Flip Effect Special Summons a Flip Monster from your Deck face-down and she can also Quick Effect flip any number of your monsters face-up or face-down. Bibliomuse can Special Summon herself back face-down after being Tributed and sent there. Her Flip Effect adds a Prediction Princess monster other than herself and a Ritual Spell from Deck to hand and while she is face-up on the field, your Ritual Monsters gain targeting and destruction protection from your opponent’s card effects. 1 Deus-X Krawler which negates all activated monster effects on your opponent's side of the field after it has been flipped face-up and if it is destroyed on field, you can search for a Level 9 monster with a different Type and Attribute. 1 Enneacraft - Astay.PIXIEA which can, when your opponent activates a card or effect that targets a card(s) you control, flip itself face-up as part of this effect’s activation in order to negate that effect and then allow you to banish a random card out of your opponent’s hand face-down. Also, after it has been flipped face-up, your opponent cannot target cards on either field or in either GY with card effects. 2 Mermail Abyssteus which can discard another WATER monster from hand to GY to Special Summon itself from your hand and when it is Special Summoned this way, you can add a Level 4 or lower Mermail monster from Deck to hand. Sadly, we are not playing my other Mermail monsters because we can’t make use of the old ones and while the new ones in Abyssrhine, the Atlantean Spirit and Mermail Shadow Squad are really really good, their best effects do lock you into WATER monsters from the Extra Deck for the rest of the turn. 1 Poseidra, the Storming Atlantean which can send 1 other WATER monster from your hand or face-up field to GY to Special Summon itself from hand and it is Normal or Special Summoned, you can send an Atlantean or Mermail monster from Deck to GY to target a card your opponent controls and return it to hand. If anything, Poseidra is an Atlantean monster who can be searched off of Neptabyss who can also send a WATER monster from hand to GY as cost for its effect which also Special Summons it from hand. While I would like to play a second copy for follow-up purposes, I would rather keep the Deck’s Poseidra to Abyssteus ratio at 1:2. You see, Abyssteus, while it can be searched through Dragoons is not an Atlantean in name, so it cannot be searched off of Neptabyss. And the reason why we need to search for Poseidra off of Neptabyss despite it also being able to activate in hand to send a WATER from hand to GY as cost for its effect is because Neptabyss cannot search itself, so we need to use Dragoons’s effect to search for Neptabyss for the combos I described earlier. If I open Diva, I don’t mind seeing Poseidra in my hand because it is not a brick in that specific combo. If I open Poseidra next to Dragoons, I’m gonna cry if I don’t also draw Abyssteus as Abyssteus is not searchable off of Neptabyss as mentioned previously. That’s why I’d rather keep the Poseidra to Abyssteus ratio as 1:2. Heck, I’d even do 1 Poseidra to 3 Abyssteus. If I am going to hard open one of them, I’d rather it be Abyssteus. 1 Adamancipator Crystal - Dragite. Say hello to our Small World bridge. It’s 0 ATK monster who is a Level 4, so any Ghost Girl handtrap, Droll, Veiler, or a non-WATER Mulcharmy can bridge to Dragite who can then bridge to Diva. You can also bridge from Neptabyss or Abyssteus into Dragite into Diva as well. 3 Atlantean Dragoons who can add a Sea Serpent monster other than itself from Deck to hand if it is sent to GY to activate a WATER monster’s effect. 3 Deep Sea Diva who can Special Summon a Level 3 or lower Sea Serpent monster from Deck when it is Normal Summoned. 3 Neptabyss, the Atlantean Prince who can send an Atalantean from Deck to GY other than another copy of himself to add an Atlantean monster from Deck to hand other than another copy of himself. Also, if he is sent to GY to activate a WATER monster’s effect, you can target an Atlantean monster in GY other than himself and Special Summon it. 3 Mulcharmy Fuwalos, 3 Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring, and 3 Droll & Lock Bird. 

For Spell/Traps: 1 Pot of Prosperity. 1 World Legacy Monstrosity which can either Special Summon a Level 9 monster from your hand or target a Level 9 monster you control to Special Summon 2 Level 9 monsters from your Deck with a different type and Attribute, but with different names. 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which can Ritual Summon a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand or GY face-up or face-down and you can banish it from GY during the Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess monster from Deck face-down. 3 Small World and 3 Infinite Impermanence. 

Extra Deck: 1 Elder Entity N’tss which can target and destroy a card on field when it is sent to the GY. 1 Ravenous Crocodragon Archethys which draws you cards when it is Synchro Summoned equal to the number of non-Tuners used for its Synchro Summon. Also, you can Quick Effect discard 2 cards to target and destroy a card on field which technically does trigger the effects of your Atlantean monsters, but you are probably not going to be doing this. 1 Ib the World Chalice Justiciar who searches for a World Legacy card on Synchro Summon. 1 Herald of the Arc Light which adds a Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell from Deck to hand when it is sent to GY. 1 THE Star Ham who can discard a card on Synchro Summon to Special Summon back a monster that was used as material for its Synchro Summon from GY as a Tuner. Also, if it is in the GY, you can discard 2 cards to Special Summon it, but it is banished when it leaves the field. 2 Mereologic Aggregator. 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity. 1 Poseidra Abyss, the Atlantean Dragon Lord which can also be Xyz Summoned using an Atlantean or Mermail Xyz Monster you control in which you transfer its materials to this card. It can detach 2 materials and send a WATER monster from hand or Deck to GY to bounce up to 3 cards your opponent controls to hand. And if it is Xyz Summoned and sent to Gy, you can discard a card to GY to Special Summon 3 Level 3 or lower Fish, Sea Serpent, or Aqua monsters from your hand and/or GY. It is wild how this effect locks you into nothing. Like, I know that I went straight into Singularity with the monsters that Poseidra Abyss Summoned, but because you are not locked into anything, you could do so much more. You can Synchro Diva, Neptabyss, and Dragoons into a Wind Pegasus @Ignister before Link Summoning something to put it into rotation for its GY effect. You could make Lib the World Key Blademaster and set World Legacy Pawns with her effect before Linking her off so that you can flip Tarotreith with Pawns and use Tarotrei’s effect for interruption. You can Link Summon 2 generic Cyberse Link Monsters and then Link them with Masquerena into Firewall Dragon Darkfluid - Neo Tempest Terahertz and then use its effect to send Cyberse Desavewurm from Extra Deck to GY, and because you are already playing a second Aggregator, Terahertz can send it from Extra Deck to Gy on your opponent’s turn for a negate. Not to mention that Desavewurm also provides a Spell/Trap negate by banishing itself from Gy while you control a LINK-4 or higher monster. Like, go wild with the stuff Poseidra Abyss can enable. 1 Abysstrite, the Atlantean Spirit who can target a Level 7 or lower Fish, Sea Serpent, or Aqua in GY on Xyz Summon and Special Summon that monster. She puts more material on field and can be used to Xyz Summon Poseidra Abyss which is just nuts. 1 Firewall Dragon Singularity which is a generic LINK-6 that can Quick Effect target cards your opponent controls up to the number of different card types (Ritual, Fusion, Synchro, Xyz) you control and in your GY and return them to hand which also boosts Singularity by 500 ATK for each. Also, if a monster it points to is destroyed by battle or sent to GY, you can target a Cyberse in your GY and Special Summon it. 3 bounces from field/GY is really good, especially since Singularity can also revive a Cyberse if a monster it points to is destroyed by battle or sent to GY. 1 S:P Little Knight and 1 I:P Masquerena. 1 Dyna Mondo who can target a card on field and a Ritual Monster in your GY and shuffle both into the Deck when it is Special Summoned. 

Side Deck: 2 Nibiru, the Primal Being, 3 Mulcharmy Purulia, 2 Ghost Belle & Haunted Mansion, 3 Lightning Storm, 1 Called by the Grave, 1 Triple Tactics Talent, and 3 Evenly Matched.

deck_description:
Main deck is simple, there's nothing really special except that you're not playing Mulcharmy Purulia. I couldn't find the space for the card and I also think that it's not a good card this format. 1 draw is not worth the Purulia. You'll also see I'm playing only Bystial Magnamhut and no other Bystials, the reason is that while there is tons of targets for Bystials when you go second, there's no space for other Bystials and if they're on things like Crystron or Dracotail, there's a high chance you won't even be able to use 'em, so to prevent that issue I play only Magnamhut since it can search for Beryl (making it kinda necessary) to give you some starting plays when you go second. It's also level 6, meaning that Sage/Maiden + Magnamhut is your Rose Moonlight Dragon which is a free bounce that can also be triggered by your opponent summoning a Dracotail fusion, a Crystron synchro, a K9, a Mitsurugi ritual etc. I also like Ghost Belle since it does stop some things in the format like Mitsurugi ritual monster's GY effect, Yummy Mignon, Yummy synchro monster's recovery, K9 Lupis, Crystron Eleskeletus, Dracotail Mululu's recovery effect etc.

For the extra deck, nothing really special going on here. It's a basic Blue-Eyes control version extra deck (rather then a very vulnerable combo version), you'll see it in tons of Blue-Eyes builds online and in the events.

Usually I don't post side decks, but I feel like I should do it this time. Currently the best decks are Crystron K9, Yummy, Dracotail, Lunalight and Mitsurugi. The side deck given is here to stop all of those. Lancea is for Crystron K9 and Lunalight, preventing them from banishing their stuff and stopping some of their plays. D.D. Crow is here actually for Crystron K9 to hit Smiger before it even activates, Yummy to banish anything Mignong might try to reborn, Dracotail to banish what Arthalion or Mululu target, Mitsurugi to banish Habakiri or Murakamo and for Lunalight to banish Yellow Marten or something Lunalight Tiger targets, or possibly even Silver Hound in some scenarios. Thrust combinations are also simple, you're looking for Dark Ruler no More against Yummy or Crystron K9; you're gonna be taking Feather Duster against Dracotail even when going first, as they'll be setting their Dracotail spells and traps during your turn, and also for Mitsurugi, sometimes even Crystron; you'll take Dimensional Barrier against probably every single deck you face as links are out of the meta with Maliss now losing almost all hope due to the last banlist and DOOD coming out. Evenly is also the best board breaker for you as you don't need your battle phase.

Overall, I really like Blue-Eyes this format. It's not the most expensive deck in the world, it can go from 250-320 $ (for my euro users, that's about 180-230 € in Europe), it can play extremely well around Fuwalos since you play 16 hand traps and play the Primite engine (basically, if they Fuwalos when you get Lordly Lode on the board with Beryl, you can search Drill Beam with Lode and then use Beryl's second effect to send Blue-Eyes to the graveyard in order to reborn it with Lode). Your boards aren't easily breakable by current best decks and post side your deck is basically unstoppable.

deck_excerpt: A unique take on a D/D deck built around Psychic End Punisher; Take on the meta with this powerhouse, but watch out for your backrow... its
deck_description:
This deck is built on setting up a strong defensive board turn 1 and passing with lots of floodgates and protection, and then summoning your boss, Psychic End Punisher on turn 3 to win the duel with an OTK. Assuming you go first, this deck consistantly beats MOST meta decks including ryzeal, blue-eyes, and dragoon. This deck is weak to opponent's that lower their lp(Maliss, P.U.N.K., D/D/D, etc...) and this deck's GREATEST weakness is backrow-removal.

 

Note: When Doom Of Dimensions TCG  releases, replace Lamia and Nighthowl with 2 copies of D/D Lance Soldier.

deck_excerpt: How does the strongest deck of all time fare against the current meta of Maliss and Ryzeal dominating Masterduel ladder?
deck_description:
How does the strongest deck of all time fare against the current meta of Maliss and Ryzeal dominating Masterduel ladder? It turns out it does really well!

Despite the many banlist hits and subsequent fall from grace, Tearlaments shrugs off common anti-Maliss and anti-Ryzeal staples like Lancea, Droll, Purulia and Fuwalos. Tearlaments can also plow through an established Maliss board with just engine as well! Ryzeal Detonator just gives Tearlament duelists plusses as "destruction" effects on Tearlament cards grant extra searches or mills. Don't believe me? Watch the video or try it yourself! I've personally reached Masters 1 abusing this advantageous match-ups, easily beating Maliss and Ryzeal going first or second, and I'm confident you can too! Despite it's power severly hampered by banlists, the Tearlaments ladies can certainly defeat ladder heavyweights! 

Tearlaments in Masterduel's 2025 September meta functions as usual, milling as possible with the combined effort of Fiendsmith, Horus, Kashtira and Tearlament cards. Make impregnable boards going first, and power through everything going second with pure engine! Mill mill mill your way to victory!

And remember... Tiaraments strongest~

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

GLHF DUELISTS!
