deck_excerpt: An Artmage list with a small Strikers Engine and an example Combo
deck_description:
Artmage with a small Strikers engine (Example combo below)

Artmage isn't a particularly strong deck, but I've recently come to love it.
While looking into Strikers as a secondary engine semi-jokingly, I've come to be positively surprised both in the fun and usefulness the Strikers engine actually provides here.
One thing I'd like to mention specifically is Sky Stiker Ace = Zero.
She's...nice? Like, when you're going into her she feels good and I do find myself enjoying her presence in the deck as a pop 1 + summon raye + roze which can then lead into another pop by using raye to link into azalea, however, the fact she forces you to deck Raye and Roze is a little questionable and if I were to actually bring this list to an important tournament, I'd probably cut Zero, Raye, Roze, and Azalea, and replace them with 2 Super Poly in Main and 2 generic fusion targets in Extra. 
Obviously this deck doesn't have any immensely powerful 1ccs, and the optimal combo in this deck is always shifting very fast depending on how many discards you have for your field spell, whether you searched Medius or drew him, what you draw off Finmel, etc.

Either way, I'll add a basic combo below to give a basic idea of how the endboards can look.

Combo (Endboard at bottom):

Requirements: Engage (or Hornet Drones) + Medius the Pure and 1 blank S/T to discard

- Activate Engage to search Hornet Drones

- Activate Hornet Drones to Summon a Token

- Link the token into Kagari

- Use Kagari's effect to re-add Hornet Drones

- Use Hornet Drones to summon a Token

- Link the Token and Kagari into Cross-Sheep

- Normal Summon Medius

- Use Medius' Effect to Special Summon Power Patron from Deck

- Use Patron's Effect to fuse with Medius into Diactorus (Important: Place Diactorus into a Zone that Cross-Sheep points to!)

- CL1 Power Patron Trigger Effect to Add Alteration CL2 Cross Sheep to Special Summon Medius

- Activate Alteration to Set the Field Spell

- Use the Field Spell to discard your blank S/T and add Graflare to your Hand

- Use Graflare's Effect to Summon him from hand and set Assault from your Deck

- Activate Assault to search Medius

- Summon Medius from your hand (the Field Spell allows you to Summon one "Medius The Pure" aside from your Normal Summon per turn)

- If you have another S/T: Discard it with your Field Spell to search Finmel and use her Effect to Summon her and Draw one card. She's a very strong negate and the draw one may be a discardable S/T. If you can't get her, proceed with the rest of the combo anyway. She's just a nice extra body I wanted to mention. Most of the time you can get her in some way.

- Now you can either use your Cross-Sheep and one of your Medius to go into Zilo, use both of your Medius to go into S:P, or use both of your Medius and Cross-Sheep to go into Accesscode Talker. I will assume Zilo for the Endboard Summary below.

 

ENDBOARD:
1x Field Spell (Grind Game Potential)

1x Zilo (3x Zone negates)

1x Graflare (1x S/T Pop)

1x Finmel (Not guaranteed, see combo - board negate and ATK halve)

1x Medius (Body, not much else lol)

2x remaining hand cards

You have 9 one card combos and 7 more 1.5 card combos as for the combos

If you already have the Crystal God Tistina you can somehow get Play of the Tistina and if you are going first you can possibly set it and on your opponent's turn to summon it while having Demigod and like that you can flip all his cards but this is to risky setup better play it on your turn and make Varudras. Finally if you are secoond and you feel it you should totaly do Liebe OTK just spam level 10 bodies inflict 2k with Gustav and attack for 6k with Liebe if you are sure it will go as planned, but ideally to feel the statisfaction of TISTINA you go second make Tistina, the Divinity that Defies Darkness using Tainted of the Tistina and Crystal God Tistina and swing for 4k twice because you detach Tainted for the effect of Divinity so it makes 2 attacks and ideally your opponent has no board left.

deck_name: Tournament Harpie Deck - WCQ Regional Rio sept 14th 2025
deck_description:
Deck piloted by me during Rio de Janeiro's WCQ Regional on september 14th 2025.

 

Scored 2 wins out of 7 matches; those were against one Blue-Eyes/Buster Blader and one Dogmatika/Shadoll Stun. Some misplays made me lose some 2 matches I could reasonable win (against yuumi/sky striker and morganite/vanity stun).

 

About the concept: Primite is by far the best engine to mix with Harpies. It avoid your dependancy on normal summon, has one-card combos, adds consistency etc. Lode's effect lets you keep XYZ Pet Dragon with his effects and materials. Unfortunely I didnt have the time to try a smaller number of cards (I was expecting 45/47), but the starting hand ratio is 1 or 2 bricks out of 15 hands, that speaks for itself.

Some regrets: 3 cards in my side were specific for Vanquish Soul, I never engaged any, it would have been better to use Scenario Rotation as side against Yummi. Money issues didnt allowed me to have: Purulia, a 3rd beryl, droplet. But I'm quite satisfied of what this deck could do considering the current meta.

Branded deck without branded fusion.
Needs some work, namely more dragons in the main

The goal of the deck is to consistently loop 3-4 times and end on Draco Future. Kanzashi is critical for the 4th and 5th loop to save your M7s. Hearld does the same when you start on Grimness as your normal. You have 15 points to do whatever you want in your side deck. There is an arguement for dropping 1 Prep and then maindecking a Called by. 

 

Been test handing this since the format announcement and it's almost always going to rip 2 cards and end on Draco (2 when you rip 4 cards). Past that will take time and practice. 4 card rips are more consistent now but you have to be thinking very far ahead.

deck_excerpt: Slapdash attempt at making a blind second Fossil build for Genesys format.
deck_description: Going second is the only way to play this deck because it's so bad. The idea is to play Skull Meister to keep monster with reborn effects to stay in the GY for fusion fuel. I wish this deck was better but it's so awful that there really is no salvaging it except for a format that lowers the power level of all the best decks. I had Purge in here but having a monster I can discard is never a bad idea. I can also play Spoly but Ultimate Slayer just serves a better purpose being able to foolish my Skull Buggy and Skullgar which can get me started by adding Weathering Soldier or Fossil Fusion. Enigmaster Packbit serves a similar purpose, allowing me to discard Weathering Solder for effect, or any other monster in hand I'd rather have in GY for a Fossil Fusion while scaling my opponent's monster at the same time.

deck_name: So you want to play Paleozoics?
deck_excerpt: 98 point 60 card Paleozoic Labrynth pile for casual Genesys format
deck_description:
This will be written with the perspective of a new player in mind, as Genesys format is designed to bring in returning players to a less complicated format.
Welcome, so you want to play Paleozoics? Paleozoic is a slow control deck that has so many tools in its toolbox between the main deck and extra deck that it can deal with almost any situation. The gameplan here is to grind your opponent out of resources with your powerful trap effects and almost endless recycling. There are no “one card combos" and every hand you draw will have a varied path towards victory. If this sounds like something you are interested in then read on as I will detail every card as well as give a short explanation and gameplay example that you can use to begin mastering this deck.

The Labrynth Package
A lineup of Lady, Arias, and Arianna. These cards are here to support a Paleozoic gameplan not a Labrynth gameplan, which is why there is no Lovely, Welcome/Big Welcome, or furniture.
While Arias is in the graveyard you are able to use it to discourage your opponent from doing something called chain blocking. This is a game mechanic in which your opponent responds to one of your trap effects in order to "block" your Paleozoics from "seeing" it, as every Paleozoic says "when" which means they must be activated directly after the activation of a trap.
Arianna is a simple searcher to add a Labrynth name that you might be missing, Archfiend will be able to add Mirror Force, and Lady is able to add anything that your heart could desire.

The Paleozoic Names
Canadia can flip your opponent's monster face down, keep in mind if your opponent is on an XYZ or Synchro deck that this will stop them from being able to use that monster as material.
Dinomischus is an excellent piece of removal that is hard for a lot of decks to deal with, and it also allows you to fill up your graveyard.
Marrella is so versatile because it can send anything you need to the graveyard that it is hard to give advice for, however some notable cards that you will want to make sure you have are Transaction Rollback and Rise to Full Height.
Olenoides main purpose is being able to recycle your Transaction Rollbacks after they have been used and your Paleozoics if they end up banished. Keep in mind that it returns any banished card, even cards that have been banished face down by something like a Kashtira Fenrir.
Anomalocaris the “boss monster” of Paleozoics, it generates you advantage as well as disrupting your opponent. However due to the slower nature of this deck you don’t want to rush this card out as soon as possible. Wait until you have summoned an Opabinia and filled up your graveyard.
Opabinia is the easily accessible searcher for this deck, you are able to access any trap through adding a Marrella with this effect. Keep in mind that Opabinia is immune to monster effects, so if you opponent wants to stop your plays with an Effect Veiler or an Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring you can sleep soundly knowing they discarded a card for no reason.

Transaction Rollback
The most flexible and valuable card in this deck, it can be anything and it can even ignore one per turn clauses on cards. Get this card into the graveyard as soon as possible and by any means possible.
The simplest way is by using any two Paleozoics to make Paleozoic Opabinia, allowing you to add Paleozoic Marrella and then immediately activate to send Transaction Rollback directly to the graveyard.

Magicolloidal Sol
This can make anything in the extra deck, which has been designed as a toolbox, but the two Paleozoic XYZ should be prioritized if possible.
However if you need to negate something you can make Toadally Awesome, or if you need removal to protect your life total you can make Merry Melffys or Sky Cavalry Centaurea.

Mirage of Nightmare
Before discarding your hand keep in mind that Paleozoic Opabinia allows you to activate Paleozoics from your hand.
If it is difficult to manage discarding your entire hand every turn, I recommend replacing it with Needlebug Nest in the side deck.

Traptantalizing Tune
Better than Pot of Greed in this deck as this will allow you to fill up your graveyard with Paleozoics as well as recycle a spent Transaction Rollback.

Balance of Judgment
Our draw trap of choice for the ability to copy it in the graveyard with Transaction Rollback while you have an empty field to fill up your entire hand. If you are finding yourself unable to maneuver through situations in which it would be beneficial, I recommend replacing it with Accumulated Fortune or Hope for Escape in the side deck.

Destructive Daruma Karma Cannon
This is one of the best playmakers the deck has to offer, it does so much heavy lifting for being such a simple effect.
If you flip a Paleozoic that has been summoned from the graveyard face down with it, it will be counted as a "new card" and will not be banished if it leaves the field.
It can remove any unaffected boss monsters as the text says that your opponent must send the card their control to the graveyard, not this trap's effect.
This is the main trap that you will want to be looping with Transaction Rollback.

Elemental Burst
You might be asking yourself how you are going to tribute a wind, water, fire, and earth monster to activate this card, well if this card and Transaction Rollback are both in the graveyard, you can activate Transaction Rollback to copy Elemental Burst without having to pay the cost.
This card is very bad to draw and you should prioritize discarding it with Paleozoic Dinomischus and Traptantalizing Tune, sending it directly to the graveyard with Paleozoic Marrella, or destroying it with Trap Holic.

Fiend Griefing
The graveyard has the nickname of "the second hand" for how many different decks abuse it, so being able to disrupt your opponent while also generating advantage for yourself by sending either Arias or Absolute King Back Jack makes this a very powerful card in this deck.

Lost Wind
A discount Infinite Impermanence, this card will only be able to affect special summoned monsters, however the monster you negate will remain that way forever, there is no "end of turn" clause here.
It can also be reused from the graveyard and recycled from banishment by Traptantalizing Tune and Paleozoic Leanchoilia.

Mirror Force
Backrow removal comes with a heavy point cost associated with it and it remains to be seen if people are willing to pay that cost, if not it will be tricky to remove the Mirror Force even if they know you have set it with Labrynth Archfiend.
If you are playing against a deck with monsters that can not be destroyed by card effects or a deck that has a lot of backrow, I recommend replacing this with Heavy Storm Duster in the side deck.

Rise to Full Height
This card is very hard to grasp in a vacuum however if you play with the deck for a while you will begin to understand the utility of it. You are able to just activate it whenever you want on your own turn if you need to summon a Paleozoic to make a play, and you are able to protect one of your monsters by giving it a massive defense buff.
A useful tip to keep in mind is that if you have two of these cards in your graveyard, and you activate both of them with each targeting a different monster, your opponent will be unable to attack you at all as there is no legal attack target.

Trap Holic and Trap Trick
These are very flexible searchers in this deck and you will be able to ignore both of their restrictions very easily.
Trap Holic does not negate your own card so you can destroy one of your own traps and still gain the effect.
And if you use Transaction Rollback to copy Trap Trick you will not be restricted to using only one more trap effect as Trap Trick says "after this card resolves" and you did not resolve Trap Trick, you resolved Transaction Rollback.
However if you are activating Trap Trick itself, keep the restriction in mind.

Waboku
While the card is designed to protect you and your Paleozoics from battle you are actually able to activate it on your own turn to potentially summon a Paleozoic from the graveyard allowing you to make an XYZ. For this reason Waboku is played over a card like Threatening Roar.

Absolute King Back Jack
A fiend that you can use to generate advantage by sending it to the graveyard with Fiend Griefing if you already have an Arias in rotation.
If Labrynth Archfiend is not working for you then you can replace it with this card.

Mischief of the Gnomes
An absolutely devastating card that has always seen some niche play, with the function of XYZ and Synchro monsters requiring specific levels of monsters to be summoned you will be able to completely shut down any non-Fusion deck with this card.
This card is extremely matchup dependent so advice is hard to give, however some suggestions on what to replace are Balance of Judgement, Mirror Force, Fiending Griefing, or Lost Wind. Just try to keep in mind which of these would not be useful in your matchup.

Extra Deck
The extra deck was designed to be as simple to understand with no crazy combos.
Merry Melffys, Sky Cavalry Centaurea, Onibimaru Soul Sweeper, and The Phantom Knights of Cursed Javelin are all different forms of removal that you can use to deal with as many potential threats your opponent can make.

Toadally Awesome, Utopic Future, and Utopic Draco Future are negates that also gain you advantage by stealing your opponents cards.

Ninja Shadow Mosquito allows you to deal a lot of damage and punish your opponent for summoning a high attack point monster.

Mannequin Cat won’t come up in every duel however when it does it can be a very easy way for you to summon a Labrynth monster from your deck.

 

Good luck :3
Not sure if spending 33 points on Grand Entrance is worth it, but having 1 to tutor sometimes with Dugg charger is important.
